 <br><a data-href="Lunch Break" href="https://alexgossalexgoss.github.io/operatorwiki/mechanics/modes/Lunch Break.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Lunch Break</a> occurs at the end of a <a data-href="shift" href="https://alexgossalexgoss.github.io/operatorwiki/mechanics/modes/shift.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">shift</a>â€™s fourth hour.<br>"Lunch" is provided to all employees at the facility."<br>
"<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="operator" data-href="operator" href="https://alexgossalexgoss.github.io/operatorwiki/characters/operator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Operators</a> are permitted to converse with each other during lunch."<br>Players can talk to other <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="operator" data-href="operator" href="https://alexgossalexgoss.github.io/operatorwiki/characters/operator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">operators</a> during the collective meal, potentially gaining information and advancing the narrative.<br><br><br>How to emphasize unfairness that feels structural and not arbitrary?<br>
How do players resist or gain small wins?<br>
How to let players cheat back?<br>
Where does the food come from?<br><br>This minigame is meant to break player <a data-href="flow" href="https://alexgossalexgoss.github.io/operatorwiki/flow" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">flow</a>, challenging and disrupting the plans and expectations for the rest of their shift and encouraging them to think about the other workers around them.<br>Further reflect world state of the game (prosperity, decline, etc.)<br>Player character (and we can assume their coworkers) must consume food in order to maintain their stats for the afternoon shift.<br>
A player must eat a minimum amount or carry out their afternoon shift hungry. This results in <a data-href="debuff" href="https://alexgossalexgoss.github.io/operatorwiki/mechanics/statuses/debuff.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">debuff</a>s. (There could also be a level of complexity added where there is a gradation in eating a balanced amount but that's complicated, do some player characters require more food for example?)<br>Besides instrumentalizing food as a numerical value within a  game mechanic, this minigame intends to have players interact with their coworkers to reveal more about their world, their shop, and each other.<br>
